    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-08-05T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-08-05T15:00:00-05:00" n="52"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.116/136: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the First
                        Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Salisbury</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">at Peiping</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-05T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 5, 1938—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>216. Tientsin’s 144, July 29, 4 p.m., and the Ambassador’s 397, August 3, 4 p.m.,
                    commenting on your 485, August 3, noon,<note n="56" xml:id="d52fn56">Latter two
                        telegrams not printed.</note> in regard to embargo on wireless equipment at
                    Tientsin and Tsingtao.</p>
                <p>With regard to Tientsin’s telegram, you may, if you consider the situation
                    warrants such action, make appropriate representations to the Japanese
                    Embassy.</p>
                <p>Department concurs in the Ambassador’s suggestion that the Tsingtao phase should
                    be taken up at Shanghai. Please inform Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
